United Kingdom 1403 / 22.5

Total 8547 / 16.8

Reported cases in 2012 are much lower than for the same period in 2011, and there was no increase in cases at the European level during the peak transmission season from February to June 2012.

The highest notification rate was among infants under one year of age (210.5 cases per 1 000 000 population), followed by children aged between one and 4 years (102.6 cases per 1 000 000 population).

Vaccination status was known for 7637 (89 percent) of the 8547 reported cases, and of these: 83 percent (6331 cases) were unvaccinated; 13 percent (978) had received one dose of measles vaccine; 4 percent (303) had received 2 or more doses; and 0.3 percent (25) had received an unknown number of doses. The proportion of unvaccinated cases was high across all age groups, including those between one and 4 years old, the age group targeted by vaccination programmes.

Ten cases were complicated by acute measles encephalitis over the last 12 months, but there were no measles-related deaths reported.

