[8] USA (WA)
Date: Thu 1 Nov 2012
Source: The Daily News online [edited]
http://tdn.com/news/local/measles-case-identified-at-woodland-primary-school/article_30b89f9a-2489-11e2-8370-0019bb2963f4.html


Woodland Primary School [Cowlitz County, Washington state] is alerting parents and guardians that a student has a case of measles, a highly contagious viral disease. Superintendent Michael Green sent home a letter with students on Thursday [1 Nov 2012] listing the symptoms and the precautions taken by the Woodland School District.

The Cowlitz County Health Department and the district have thoroughly reviewed the immunization history of every student at Woodland Primary School and found 25 students who must be excluded from school due to either not being vaccinated for mumps, measles and rubella (the MMR vaccine) or to only having had one of the 2 required doses.

"We are taking serious precautions to notify everyone of this situation and make you aware of our efforts," Green wrote. "The district is offering a free immunization clinic on Mon 5 Nov 2012 for students who have only had one shot." After receiving shots, a student may return to school, but if symptoms develop despite the shot, the student must stay home.

The child with measles may have been exposed to the virus while on a trip to California, said Hilary Gillette-Walch of the county's health department. The child has not been hospitalized, she said. Green said the district is closely following Health Department guidelines to control measles in the school setting.

Measles signs and symptoms appear 7-14 days after exposure to the virus, according to the Mayo Clinic website. They include: fever, dry cough, runny nose, sore throat, inflamed eyes (conjunctivitis), sensitivity to light, tiny white spots with bluish-white centers found inside the mouth on the inner lining of the cheek, and a skin rash made up of large, flat blotches that often flow into one another.

Globally, measles remains one of the leading causes of vaccine-preventable death among children, killing more than 100 000 children in the world each year, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). In 2000, measles was declared eliminated in the United States, but measles continues to be imported, the CDC said. Last year [2011], there were 222 measles cases reported in the U.S. and 17 measles outbreaks (defined as 3 or more cases linked in time and place).

The last cases of measles in Cowlitz County were reported in 1999.

[Byline: Leslie Slape]

